LR_Attrition

Pinak Kapalay

February 28, 2019

Problem Statement : To study the following data, analyze it and predict which employee is likely to undergo Attrition and which not. Make the best possible model so that when applied to the future set of data, would generate acceptable results.

Solution : The above statement comes under the category of classification problem which can be solved using either of the Logistic Regression, Support Vector Machine, Decision Tree and Random Forest classification Algorithms.

The Logistic Regression Algorithm for the problem statement is as follows:

Comments: Finding the numbers of the previously detected outliers and their upper and lower cutoff for each variable.

out_std_check = function(x,f){
  q1 = quantile(x,0.25, na.rm = TRUE)
  q3 = quantile(x,0.75, na.rm = TRUE)
  iqr = q3-q1
  lc=q1-f*iqr
  uc=q3+f*iqr
  n=sum(x>uc | x<lc)
  #return n
  val=list(num=n,lower_cutoff=lc,upper_cutoff=uc)
  return(val)
}

Comments: Capping th outliers by imputing them with the upper and lower cut-off in order to make the data distribution fair i.e remove skewness if any.

attr_out_impute <- function(x,f){
  
  q1 = quantile(x,0.25, na.rm = TRUE)
  q3 = quantile(x,0.75, na.rm = TRUE)
  iqr = q3-q1
  lc = q1-f*iqr
  uc = q3+f*iqr
  
  for (j in 1:length(x)) {
    if(x[j]<lc)
    {x[j] <- lc}
    else if(x[j]>uc)
    {x[j] <- uc}
    else
    {}
    }
   return(x) 
}
